    <p class="text-left text-sm text-slate-500">
      <strong>Net IRR</strong>:  Gross IRR represents the cumulative investment-related cash flows for a given fund (and not any one investor in the fund), on the basis of the actual timing of investment inflows and outflows (for unrealized investments assuming disposition at the end of the relevant fiscal quarter or other date specified) aggregated on a gross basis quarterly, and the return is annualized and compounded before management fees and certain other fund expenses and measures the returns on the fund's investments as a whole without regard to whether all of the returns would, if distributed, be payable to the fund's investors. In addition, gross IRRs at the fund level differ from those at the individual investor level as a result of, among other factors, timing of investor-level inflows and outflows. Gross IRR does not represent the return to any fund investor.
    </p>
    <p class="text-left text-sm text-slate-500">
      Net IRR means the gross IRR applicable to the Fund as a whole, including returns for related parties which may not pay fees, net of management fees, certain fund expenses, all offset to the extent of interest income, and measures returns at the Fund level on amounts that, if distributed, would be paid to investors in the Fund. In addition, net IRR at the Fund level will differ from that at the individual investor level as a result of, among other factors, timing of investor-level inflows and outflows. Net IRR does not represent the return to any fund investor.
    </p>
    <p class="text-left text-sm text-slate-500">
      The Net IRR presented above represents the Fund's projected Fund-level returns and assumes (i) the Fund purchases Loans bearing 15% interest; (ii) annual Management Fees and Fund expenses of 2.5%; (iii) no loan losses; (iv) no leverage; (v) continued consumer and business demand for the loans at the 15% interest rate; and (vi) total Fund assets grow and remain at a size that adequately covers additional annual Fund operating expenses.  A number of factors could cause any of the foregoing assumptions to be incorrect, in which case the Fund's projected Net IRR may be lower, and the Fund may lose money.
    </p>
